Content: If the computer reads in order, and we show it the cough function first, how does it know what the cough(); does before it gets down to the function underneath?

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: `void cough(void);` is a function prototype.  It tells the compiler that the function exists (and will be defined later) so that when it reads the call `cough()` further down, it won't be flagged as unknown.

Author: Ristray#9849
Content: So it still reads the cough() second but waits until it passes by the function later before deciding to complain about it?

Author: Ristray#9849
Content: Maybe I'm just trying to get too specific about how this stuff works and just accept it happens somehow.

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: by putting the prototype at the top, you are "promising" to the compiler that a function called `cough` exists

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: just like all the other functions in your program that come from the included libraries

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: like printf.

Content: Oh. ok, that works. Thanks.

Author: Coupe2T#8639
Content: clang and make just compile your code,  When you did make hello, it recognised your hello file and compiled, and you then ran it with ./hello and it produced the expected output right?  then you tried to run clang, and you have basically said said clang {compile} into a program named {-o} a program called {string} from my file called {string.c} and include the library cs50 {lcs50}.  It is erroring as you have no file called string.c.  You are still using the file called hello.c.  so if you ran clang -o hello hello.c -lcs50 it should compile fine, and then you can use ./hello to test.

Author: Fa#5568
Content:
> clang and make just compile your code,  When you did make hello, it recognised your hello file and compiled, and you then ran it with ./hello and it produced the expected output right?  then you tried to run clang, and you have basically said said clang {compile} into a program named {-o} a program called {string} from my file called {string.c} and include the library cs50 {lcs50}.  It is erroring as you have no file called string.c.  You are still using the file called hello.c.  so if you ran clang -o hello hello.c -lcs50 it should compile fine, and then you can use ./hello to test.
